  {"id":"fqa-netsuke-016","type":"forensic_qa","category":"netsuke","difficulty":"expert","question":"How does provenance from major Western collections affect netsuke valuation?","answer":"Western collection provenance profoundly impacts netsuke valuation through several mechanisms: the Behrens, Hindson, Bushell, Brockhaus, and Meinertzhagen collections are recognized benchmarks. Pieces from these collections carry 50-200% price premiums over comparable uncollected examples. The mechanism: these collectors were highly selective, establishing quality standards through decades of connoisseurship; their collection catalogs provide published photographic records enabling verification; passage through recognized dealers (Sydney Moss, Eskenazi) adds additional provenance weight; and exhibition history at major museums (V&A, British Museum, MFA Boston) provides institutional validation. For authentication, collection stamps, dealer labels, and catalog numbers can be verified against published records. However, forgers have begun fabricating provenance documentation — fake collection labels and invented dealer histories. Verification through multiple independent sources is essential.","evidence":["International Netsuke Society provenance databases","Major collection sale catalogs"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["provenance","western-collections","valuation","netsuke"]},
  {"id":"fqa-netsuke-017","type":"forensic_qa","category":"netsuke","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"What are the key subject categories in netsuke and their relative market values?","answer":"Netsuke subjects fall into several categories with varying market dynamics: Animals — the most popular category. Rats, tigers, horses, and mythical creatures (dragon, kirin) are favorites. Quality of naturalistic observation distinguishes masterworks. Human figures — genre scenes, mythological characters, entertainers. Humor and narrative quality drive value. Masks — miniature versions of Noh and Kyogen masks. Technical virtuosity in expressing multiple emotions (from different viewing angles) is prized. Natural subjects — shells, gourds, mushrooms, insects. Requires extraordinary observation and carving skill. Erotica (shunga netsuke) — explicit content, a niche collecting category with dedicated following. Trick netsuke (karakuri) — with moving parts or hidden compartments. Extremely rare and valuable. Value hierarchy is driven by: carving quality over subject matter; but certain subject-carver combinations command exceptional premiums (Tomotada cattle, Okatomo animals, Masanao snails). The most valuable netsuke combine an appealing subject with masterful carving, genuine patina, and prestigious provenance.","evidence":["Davey, Netsuke: A Comprehensive Study","Bonhams netsuke sale analysis"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["subjects","categories","valuation","market"]},
  {"id":"fqa-architecture-016","type":"forensic_qa","category":"architecture","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"How does washi (traditional paper) analysis authenticate architectural elements?","answer":"Washi — handmade Japanese paper — is integral to traditional architecture in shoji screens, fusuma panels, and wall coverings. Authentication through paper analysis: Fiber identification — kozo (paper mulberry), gampi, and mitsumata fibers are identifiable under magnification. Each has distinctive morphology and confers different paper qualities. Period indicators — pre-Meiji washi is exclusively handmade with characteristic long fiber distribution; machine-made paper (post-1870s) shows uniform short fibers. Thickness variation — handmade washi shows natural thickness variation from the sugeta (screen mold) technique; machine paper is uniform. Watermarks — some prestigious paper producers used watermarks identifiable to specific workshops and periods. Sizing agents — dousa (alum and animal glue) sizing on traditional washi differs from modern sizing agents detectable through chemical analysis. For architectural authentication, the paper in shoji and fusuma is typically replaced periodically, but original paper may survive in protected areas, providing dating evidence for the architectural framework.","evidence":["Washi papermaking tradition documentation","Japanese Paper Conservation Society"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["washi","paper","shoji","architectural-materials"]},
  {"id":"fqa-contemporary-017","type":"forensic_qa","category":"contemporary","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"How does the Japanese art market structure differ from Western markets?","answer":"The Japanese domestic art market has several distinctive features affecting authentication and valuation: Department store galleries — traditionally the primary sales venue for established Japanese artists. Mitsukoshi, Takashimaya, and Isetan maintain art departments that serve as both galleries and authenticators. This system provides documentation trails but also creates potential conflicts of interest. Iemoto system — in calligraphy and certain ceramic traditions, the head of a school (iemoto) controls authentication for that tradition. Art associations (bijutsu dantai) — juried exhibitions (Nitten, Inten) establish market hierarchy. Acceptance into major exhibitions directly impacts artist pricing. Gallery system — primary market galleries in Tokyo (Ginza), Kyoto, and Osaka maintain long-term artist relationships. Secondary market — auction houses (Shinwa, Mainichi, Est-Ouest) handle resale. Japanese auction premiums and guarantees differ from Western houses. Online disruption — Yahoo! Auctions Japan is a major channel for mid-market Japanese art, creating both opportunities and authentication risks. Understanding this structure is essential for evaluating provenance claims and assessing whether documentation is credible.","evidence":["Art Basel/UBS Japan market analysis","Japan Art Dealers Association structure"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["market-structure","japan","galleries","auction"]},
